Were you the one who brought up jaws potentially shrinking?
Because I thought about that recently and thought of an evolutionary phenomenon known as "neoteny". That is what happened to humans, who have much smaller jaws than chimps or gorillas, which in turn have (proportinally) smaller jaws than baboons and mandrills.

Being bipedal and having hands would make them rely less on their teeth, so their jaws could regress to the proportion their juvenile animal counterparts would have.

Anonymous Fri 05 Mar 2021 16:10:31 No.36831799 Report
Quoted By: >>36831831 >>36832589 >>36833333
>>36817979
The decline of Trek started with Voyager. Frankly, it's a miracle it lasted as long as it did. By all logic the movies should have been shit, and TNG should have been shit. Trek fans like to put salt on all snails, as we say, but the fact that the TOS movies were mature feature films with enough balls to try new things isn't what you'd expect from a revived budget sci-fi show. A lot of people think TMP is too slow, but the sheer guts to say "yes, we're making a 2 hour slow burn about how the virile action man from the show is doubting himself in middle age, fuck you" is astounding.

And then TNG had a rocky start, it changed up the old formula to go from action/adventure stuff to an old, bald Captain who likes talking to people in beige rooms... and it's some of the best television ever. Straight up another revolutionary show that probably changed the world for the better. Then came DS9, and now you get some fan division, but it's another thing that's just ballsy as hell. Setting the space exploration show in a space station? Developing minor species into their own thing? Recurring villains and stepping away from episodic content? Holding the entire driving ideology of Star Trek to a harsher light? Yet there you go, more great television.

But with Voyager, the magic was gone. It has this fairly good setup, and it has its own moments of brilliance, but it just never has that driving force we see with its predecessors. It doesn't have any balls. It just wants to be TNG all over again, but it just doesn't have the dedication. Same thing with Enterprise, except it ironically rights some of the wrongs of Voyager.

As for Galaxy Quest and The Orville, point is more that Trek comedy isn't new. Lower Decks doesn't have to reinvent the wheel or anything. But the episodes I've seen (first 4 or something) have all been this stereotypical fast-talking sugar high comedy, and I just fucking hate it. The show and its setting really exist independently from each other.
